You need to make your regex lazy, use `(.*?)` 

***Ref :-*** [`Regex lazy qunatifiers`](http://www.rexegg.com/regex-quantifiers.html#lazy_solution)

    \[FONT=(.*?)\](.*?)

[`Regex demo`](https://regex101.com/r/25WJIP/1/)

---

    $re = &#39;/\[FONT=(.*?)\](.*?)/m&#39;;
    $str = &#39;[FONT=arial]Dit is een tekst [FONT=Courier New]nonononon&#39;;
    $subst = &#39;$2&#39;;
    
    $result = preg_replace($re, $subst, $str);

Outputs

    Dit is een tekst nonononon

You don&#39;t need any capture group. You may use this regex to match and remove what you don&#39;t want:

    $old = &#39;[FONT=arial]Dit is een tekst [FONT=Courier New]nonononon&#39;;
    $new = preg_replace(&#39;/\[FONT=[^]]*]/&#39;, &#39;&#39;, $old);
    echo &quot;$new\n&quot;;

&lt;p/&gt;

    Dit is een tekst nonononon

`[^]]` is a negated character class that will match any character that is not `]`.

